57 an approved EMSP course as defined by rules of the Board of
58 Healthdepartment, successfully pass the appropriate level
59 licensure examination as determined by the Board of
60 Healthdepartment, and submit an application to the
61 boarddepartment. An approved EMSP course for any level shall
62 be a course conforming to the curriculum for that level as
63 approved by the United States Department of Transportation, or
64 approved by any other federal agency as, in the future, may
65 takehave jurisdiction over EMSP training curriculum
66 development. A curriculum may be required to be supplemented
67 with additional modules: (i) if the modules are optional
68 modules approved by the United States Department of
69 Transportation, or itsa successor as specified above,; and
70 (ii) the optional modules are prescribed, by rule, by the
71 boarddepartment pursuant to the Alabama Administrative
72 Procedure Act.
73 (d)(1) The department shall accept, upon satisfactory
74 presentation by the applicant, education, training, and
75 experience completed while a member of the Armed Forces or
76 Reserves of the United States or the National Guard, Military
77 Reserves, or Naval Militia of any state, and proof of
78 successful passage of the National Registry of Emergency
79 Medical Technicians examination as credit toward the
80 qualifications for EMSP licensure.
81 (2) The department shall adopt rules to implement this
82 subsection.
83 (d)(e) No air or ground ambulance shall be operated for
84 ambulance purposes, and no individual shall fly, drive,
